            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Here are some of the most recent AI developments being reported right now (as of early March 2026), across industry, policy, and research:\n\n- **AI is shifting from “capability races” to deployment + monetization.** Coverage highlights companies emphasizing real-world reliability, enterprise deals, subscription tiers, and API pricing as they try to build sustainable businesses—not just bigger models.【6:0†source】\n\n- **Legal risk is rising from “hallucinated” citations and filings.** One high-profile example: a Connecticut Supreme Court matter where attorneys acknowledged using generative AI that produced fabricated case citations/quotes in a brief, renewing warnings about verification and professional responsibility when using AI in legal practice.【6:0†source】\n\n- **Big competition around AI “shopping/research” assistants.** Meta is reported to be testing an AI shopping research feature in its chatbot, positioning it against similar product-discovery experiences in ChatGPT and Google Gemini.【6:0†source】\n\n- **More “agent frameworks” and developer tooling are being open-sourced.** Recent reports mention releases like ByteDance’s DeerFlow 2.0 (an open-source “SuperAgent” framework), Alibaba’s OpenSandbox (a sandbox platform for AI app development), and other “agent skills/toolkits” trending on GitHub—signaling continued focus on agents that can use tools, run code, and execute multi-step workflows.【6:3†source】\n\n- **Ongoing research headlines: AI in healthcare + ethics concerns.** Science coverage includes work warning about ethical issues when people use chatbots for therapy-style advice, alongside continued progress in medical imaging AI (e.g., rapid MRI interpretation) and other applied systems.【6:4†source】\n\nIf you tell me what you mean by “latest news” (business deals, new models, regulation, or research breakthroughs), I can narrow this to the top 5–10 items in that category.",
